# Offices of State titles from the Middle Ages

Titles of the Welsh Court are the titles of the various Offices of State used in [Wales](/Wales_in_the_Early_Middle_Ages) during the [Middle Ages](/Middle_Ages). The roles of different officers changed over time, and these changes may reflect the political developments in the centuries before and after the death of [Llywelyn ap Gruffudd](/Llywelyn_ap_Gruffudd) in 1282. The Welsh title *distain*, being derived from “dish thane”,[^1] indicates that he was originally concerned with the royal dishes at table, but it is known that [Ednyfed Fychan](/Ednyfed_Fychan), Distain to Llywelyn, was effectively a [prime minister](/Prime_minister) who did not regularly wait on the ruler at table. Over the course of the medieval period the functional evolution of these offices mirrors the shifting power dynamics between the Welsh princes, the Norman Marcher lords, and later the English Crown, producing a layered administrative hierarchy that blended Celtic tradition with Anglo‑Norman governance.  

[^1]: [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed)

The terminology itself is a linguistic palimpsest: *distain* comes from the Old English *dish* (meaning “dish”) and *thane* (a noble retainer), suggesting an early association with the provision of food and the management of the royal household’s culinary affairs. Yet the practical remit of the *distain* expanded far beyond the kitchen, encompassing fiscal oversight, diplomatic protocol, and even intelligence gathering. This duality is evident in the way later offices were reframed under Norman influence, adopting Latin‑derived titles while retaining native Welsh semantics.  

## The Royal Family

The dynastic structure of medieval Wales was fluid, with titles that denoted both sovereignty and subordinate leadership.  

- • [Brenin](/King) , meaning "King" – the supreme sovereign who claimed authority over the whole of Wales, though actual control could be fragmented among competing princes.  
- • [Tywysog](/Tywysog) , meaning "Chief" or "Prince". A king was by default also a chief, but a chief was not necessarily also a king. The title *Tywysog* is thought to share a common root with the [Irish](/Irish_language) term [Taoiseach](/Taoiseach), reflecting a broader Celtic pattern of leadership terminology.  
- • [Edling](/Edling) , was a title designating the [heir to the throne](/Heir_to_the_throne). This title was borrowed from the [Old English](/Old_English_language) title [Æþeling](/%C3%86theling) meaning "royal son", underscoring the Anglo‑Saxon influence on Welsh succession practices.  

The concept of *edling* was not always hereditary in the strict sense; it could be conferred upon a promising male relative or even a distinguished cousin, serving both as a political buffer and as a means of cementing alliances through marriage.  

## Twelve Principal Officers of the Court

The court of a Welsh prince was staffed by a cadre of specialists whose titles reveal a blend of military, judicial, religious, and ceremonial duties. Each officer was attached to a specific function, and many of these positions were hereditary or could be sold, reflecting the feudal nature of Welsh society.  

- • Penteulu , literally meaning "household head" was the title given to the [captain](/Captain_(land)) of the household troops or [bodyguards](/Bodyguard). It was a position usually filled by a member of the royal family and one which conferred a responsibility on the bearer to defend the ruler; a [feudal](/Feudal) [Minister of Defence](/Minister_of_Defence). The *penteulu* commanded the elite retinue that accompanied the prince on campaign, acted as a personal bodyguard, and often served as a liaison between the prince and his noble vassals.  
- • Offeiriad Teulu , literally "household priest", a senior religious advisor. This cleric oversaw the spiritual welfare of the household, conducted rituals, and managed the court’s liturgical calendar, ensuring that religious observances aligned with both Celtic traditions and emerging Norman ecclesiastical practices.  
- • Distain , meaning "steward" from the Old English term for "dish [thane](/Thegn)". Later this office name was replaced with the term [Seneschal](/Seneschal) and came to be the principal [diplomat](/Diplomat) and executive of the court: a feudal [prime minister](/Prime_minister) and [foreign minister](/Foreign_minister). The *distain* supervised the prince’s finances, negotiated treaties, and represented the court in external affairs, effectively acting as the chief administrator of the realm.  
- • Brawdwr Llys , meaning "court [judge](/Judge)" — a senior legal officer who arbitrated on affairs of the realm; a feudal [Minister of Justice](/Minister_of_Justice). The *brawdwr llys* presided over legal disputes, interpreted customary law, and issued judgments that were binding across the prince’s territories, thereby reinforcing the rule of law in a decentralized society.  
- • Penhebogydd , the chief [falconry](/Falconry). This specialist oversaw the training and maintenance of hawks and falcons, an essential pursuit for hunting and for displaying aristocratic refinement.  
- • Pencynydd , the chief huntsman (more literally "master of the hounds"). The *pencynydd* organized the chase, coordinated the kennels, and ensured that the hunt adhered to the strict codes of courtesy and sport that were central to noble culture.  
- • Gwas Ystafell , the [chamberlain](/Chamberlain_(office)). The *gwas ystafell* managed the inner chambers of the palace, supervised domestic staff, and controlled access to the prince’s private spaces, acting as a gatekeeper of both security and privacy.  
- • Bardd Teulu , the household [bard](/Bard). The *bardd teulu* composed poetry and genealogies, preserved oral history, and served as a cultural propagandist, reinforcing the legitimacy of the ruling dynasty through verse.  
- • Drysor Neuadd , the doorkeeper of the royal hall, an honorific military rank. This officer guarded the main entrance, regulated the flow of visitors, and could summon the guard in times of threat, embodying the martial aspect of hospitality.  
- • Drysor Ystafell , the doorkeeper of the royal chamber, another honorific military rank. The *drysor ystafell* protected the inner sanctum where the prince rested, ensuring that only trusted attendants could enter the private quarters.  
- • Gwastrawd Afwyn , the groom of the rein. This attendant tended to the prince’s horses, managed the reins, and coordinated the movement of the mounted retinue during ceremonies and campaigns.  
- • Meddyg , the court [physician](/Physician). The *meddyg* provided medical care, employed herbal remedies, and advised on health matters, blending traditional Celtic healing practices with knowledge imported from continental Europe.  

These offices collectively formed a bureaucratic framework that enabled the Welsh prince to project authority across a fragmented terrain, negotiate with external powers, and maintain internal cohesion among a network of semi‑autonomous nobles.  

